<body>
<p>I read with great interest the very instructive review article by Angelidis and colleagues on “Ghrelin: New Insights Into Female Reproductive System.”<sup>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1933719112459242">1</xref>
</sup> Yet, I feel it is worthwhile to add that there is now clear evidence that exogenous ghrelin suppresses the secretion of the gonadotropins luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) not only in men<sup>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr2-1933719112459242">2</xref>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr3-1933719112459242"/>–<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr4-1933719112459242">4</xref>
</sup> but also in women.<sup>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr5-1933719112459242">5</xref>
</sup> Several findings support the assumption that ghrelin suppresses the secretion of these gonadotropins in women also under physiological circumstances: ghrelin plasma levels in physically active females with amenorrhea or menstrual disturbances were repeatedly found to be significantly higher than in those with ovoluatory cycles.<sup>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr6-1933719112459242">6</xref>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr7-1933719112459242"/>–<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr8-1933719112459242">8</xref>
</sup> Of note, in 2 of these studies, plasma levels of leptin, a known stimulant of the hypothalamic–pituitary–gonadal (HPG) axis,<sup>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr9-1933719112459242">9</xref>
</sup> did not differ between groups.<sup>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr6-1933719112459242">6</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr8-1933719112459242">8</xref>
</sup> For example, ghrelin plasma levels were 85% higher in exercising women with amenorrhea than in exercising women with ovoluatory cycles, whereas BMI, body fat, and leptin plasma levels were similar.<sup>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr6-1933719112459242">6</xref>
</sup>
</p>
<p>Considering these findings, it appears very likely that the hunger hormone ghrelin, being increased in undernutrition,<sup>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr10-1933719112459242">10</xref>
</sup> plays a major role in suppressing the HPG axis in states of energy restriction.<sup>
<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr11-1933719112459242">11</xref>
</sup>
</p>
<p>In conclusion, there is evidence that ghrelin suppresses the secretion of gonadotropins in women.</p>
